## Structural Preservation
- Preserve the logical reading order (left-to-right, top-to-bottom for multi-column layouts)
- Maintain hierarchical structure with proper heading levels (h1, h2, h3, etc.)
- Keep paragraph boundaries and section breaks intact
{% if not singlePageOnly %}
- Handle multi-page documents by preserving page flow and section continuity
{% endif %}

## Table Handling
- Convert all tables to proper HTML table markup using `<table>`, `<thead>`, `<tbody>`, `<th>`, and `<td>` elements
- Preserve column alignment and spanning where visible
- Include table captions if present
- Maintain data relationships and structure across page breaks

## Mathematical Content
- Convert mathematical equations to HTML using:
  - HTML entities for simple symbols (×, ÷, ±, ≤, ≥, ∞, α, β, γ, etc.)
  - `<sup>` and `<sub>` for superscripts and subscripts
  - MathML for complex equations when possible
  - Plain text with clear formatting as fallback
- Preserve equation numbering and references

## Academic Elements
- Mark abstracts with `<section class="abstract">`
- Use `<figure>` and `<figcaption>` for figures and their captions
- Convert references and citations to proper links where applicable
- Preserve author names, affiliations, and publication details
- Handle footnotes and endnotes appropriately
- Maintain bibliography formatting

## Content to Ignore
- Page numbers, headers, and footers
- Watermarks or background elements
- Navigation elements not part of the main content
- Publisher logos or branding

## Multi-Page Processing
- Combine content from all pages into a single coherent HTML document
- Ensure section headings span properly across page breaks
- Maintain figure and table numbering across pages
- Handle continued paragraphs and sentences across pages

## Output Requirements
- Return ONLY the HTML content, no markdown code blocks or explanations
- Use semantic HTML5 elements where appropriate (article, section, header, main, etc.)
- Include minimal inline CSS only if absolutely necessary for layout preservation
- Ensure the HTML is well-formed and valid
- Structure as a complete HTML document with proper DOCTYPE, head, and body elements

